{"title_page": "USS Liberty (AGTR-5)", "text_new": "{{Other ships|Liberty (ship)}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=USS Liberty (AGTR-5) underway in Chesapeake Bay on 29 July 1967 (K-39927).jpg\n|Ship image size=300px\n|Ship caption=USS ''Liberty'' (AGTR-5) in Chesapeake Bay, 29 July 1967\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1945}}\n|Ship name= SS ''Simmons Victory''\n|Ship namesake= [[Simmons College]] in [[Boston]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder= [[Oregon Shipbuilding Corporation|Oregon Shipbuilding Corp.]]\n|Ship laid down= 23 February 1945\n|Ship launched= 6 April 1945\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship completed= 4 May 1945\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship owner= War Shipping Administration\n|Ship operator= Coastwise (Pacific Far East) Line (during WW II only)\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate= Transferred to US Navy in 1963\n|Ship status=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge= \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1968}}\n|Ship name= USS ''Liberty''\n|Ship namesake=Localities named \"Liberty\" in ten US states\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder= \n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship acquired= 25 March 1963\n|Ship commissioned=30 December 1964\n|Ship decommissioned=1 June 1968\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service= June 1967 \n|Ship struck=1 June 1970\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=Damaged beyond economical repair by Israeli attack in June 1967; sold for scrap in 1973\n|Ship status=\n|Ship homeport=[[Norfolk, Virginia]]\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge= [[File:USS Liberty (AGTR-5) insignia, 1964 (NH 83352-KN).png|150px]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship displacement=7725&nbsp;tons (light displacement)\n|Ship length={{convert|139|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|18.9|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft={{convert|7|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=Westinghouse steam turbines, single shaft, 8500 horsepower (6.3&nbsp;MW)\n|Ship speed={{convert|17.5|knot|km/h}} maximum sustained, 21&nbsp;knots emergency\n|Ship range={{convert|12,500|nmi|abbr=on}} at {{convert|12|kn}}\n|Ship complement=*62 Merchant Marine and 28 US Naval Armed Guards as Victory ship{{fact|date=February 2019}} \n*358 officers and enlisted for USS ''Liberty''\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship aircraft=none\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship armament= *1 \u00d7 [[5\"/38 caliber gun|5 in (127&nbsp;mm)/38 cal. gun]] as Victory ship \n*1 \u00d7 [[3\"/50 caliber gun|3 in (76&nbsp;mm)/50 cal. gun]]\n*8 \u00d7 [[Oerlikon 20&nbsp;mm cannon|20 mm Oerlikon]]\n*4 x [[M2_Browning|M2 Browning .50 caliber machine gun]] as USS ''Liberty'' \n|Ship notes=<ref>{{Cite journal |author=[[Babcock & Wilcox]] |date=April 1944 |title=Victory Ships |journal=Marine Engineering and Shipping Review}}</ref><ref name=danfs>{{cite web |url=https://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/l/liberty-agtr-5-iii.html |title=US Navy History, Liberty III (AGTR-5) 1964-1970 |date=29 May 2017 |last=Cressman |first=Robert J. |publisher=US Navy |accessdate=13 February 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n|}\n\n'''USS ''Liberty'' (AGTR-5)''' was a [[USS Belmont (AGTR-4)|''Belmont''-class]] [[technical research ship]] (electronic [[spy ship]]) that was [[USS Liberty incident|attacked by Israel Defense Forces]] during the 1967 [[Six-Day War]]. She was originally built and served in [[World War II]] as a VC2-S-AP3 type [[Victory ship|Victory]] cargo ship named '''SS ''Simmons Victory'''''.<ref name=danfs/><ref name=VS>{{cite web |last=Colton |first=Tim |title=Victory Ships |url=http://shipbuildinghistory.com/merchantships/2victoryships.htm |work=ShipbuildingHistory.com |publisher=The Colton Company |date=21 November 2009 |accessdate=13 February 2019}}</ref> Her keel was laid down on 23 February 1945, under a [[United States Maritime Commission|Maritime Commission]] contract at [[Oregon Shipbuilding Corporation]] of [[Portland, Oregon]].<ref name=danfs/>\n\n==Service history==\n===War Shipping Administration/[[United States Maritime Commission|Maritime Commission]]/[[United States Maritime Administration|Maritime Administration]] Years===\n\nThe ship was delivered to the [[War Shipping Administration]] on 4 May 1945.<ref name=danfs/> The next day, she was transferred to the \"Coastwise (Pacific Far East) Line\" and designated as a \"Fleet Issue Ship\".<ref name=danfs/> Her complement included a 17-man [[United States Navy Armed Guard|Navy Armed Guard]] detachment to operate the ship's [[artillery battery|gun battery]]; a three- or four-man communication liaison detachment; and 16 Navy enlisted people serving as \"winchmen and hatchmen\".<ref name=danfs/>\n\nSS ''Simmons Victory'' was tasked with delivering [[ammunition]], which was loaded at the San Francisco-area navy munitions depot at [[Port Chicago, California|Port Chicago]] for [[Operation Downfall]], the invasion of Japan.<ref name=Gillen>{{cite book |last=Gillen |first=Michael |title=Merchant Marine Survivors of World War II: Oral Histories of Cargo Carrying Under Fire |date=2015 ||chapter=Harry A. Morgan: Walnuts and Bauxite for the War |publisher=McFarland & Co. |pages=118,119, 190}}</ref> According to Harry Morgan, who served as an [[Engine officer|engineer]] on the ship, the ''Simmons Victory'' arrived in the Philippines about six weeks before [[Victory in Europe Day|V-E Day]] on 8 May 1945.<ref name=Gillen/>{{efn-la|Morgan says the ''Simmons Victory'' took on ammunition just two weeks before the [[Port Chicago disaster|disastrous explosion at Port Chicago]] on 17 July 1944, an event that occurred months before the ship was launched.}} She made one trip north in support of Operation Downfall and returned to the [[Philippines]].<ref name=Gillen/>{{efn-la|According to Morgan, the ship \"had been equipped to supply the [[United States Sixth Fleet#History|Sixth Fleet]] when they made the invasion into Japan.\" However, the US Sixth Fleet was based in the Mediterranean during World War II. The [[Sixth_United_States_Army#History|Sixth Army]] and the [[United States Seventh Fleet#History|Seventh Fleet]] were based in the west Pacific area and both were tasked to participate in Operation Downfall.}} She was in the [[Leyte Gulf]] when Japan surrendered on 15 August 1945.<ref name=Gillen/>\n\n''Simmons Victory'' departed the Leyte Gulf on 6 October 1945, en route to the US West Coast via [[Eniwetok]], and dumped ammunition at sea two days later.<ref name=danfs/>{{efn-la|Morgan says, after the war, the ''Simmons Victory'' unloaded its cargo of ammunition in Port Chicago. The official Navy account by Cressman seems to indicate that the cargo was dumped at sea: \"With a cargo of ammunition, ''Simmons Victory'' cleared Leyte Gulf on 6 October 1945, and as part of the preparation for the disarming the vessel, the armed guard dumped the ammo at sea on 8 October.\" Possibly, only the ammo on deck for the ship's gun battery was dumped at sea and the ammo carried as cargo was returned to Port Chicago.}} She arrived in San Francisco on 3 November 1945 and departed for the US east coast on 9 December 1945, reaching New York on Christmas Day, 1945.<ref name=danfs/>{{efn-la|Morgan says, after leaving Port Chicago, she took supplies to Baltimore through the [[Panama Canal]].}} Her 5-inch, 3-inch, and 20-mm guns were removed there on 9 January 1946.<ref name=danfs/>\n\nFrom December 1946 until 1963, the ship moved back and forth several times from commercial [[Bareboat charter|charters]] as a [[break bulk cargo]] carrier to stints in the [[National Defense Reserve Fleet]] (being twice berthed in the [[Hudson River]]).<ref name=danfs/> Most notably during this time, she made nine trips between November 1950 and December 1952 to the Far East during the [[Korean War]] \"to equip American troops fighting communist North Korea\" in the [[Military_Sealift_Command#Military_Sea_Transportation_Service|Military Sea Transportation Service]].<ref name=danfs/><ref name=scott>{{cite book |last=Scott |first=James |date=2009 |title=The Attack on the Liberty: The Untold Story of Israel's Deadly 1967 Assault on a U.S. Spy Ship |publisher=Simon & Schuster |isbn=978-1-4165-5482-0}}</ref><ref>[http://koreanwar-educator.org/topics/merchant_marine/index.htm Korean War Educator, Merchant Marine, Accounts of the Korean War]</ref><ref>Small United States and United Nations Warships in the Korean War, By Paul M. Edwards</ref> On 11 June 1958, ''Simmons Victory'' once again entered the National Defense Reserve Fleet, being berthed this time at Olympia, Washington, where she remained until 1963.<ref name=danfs/>\n\n===US Navy years===\n{{Ship call sign|N|I|R|Y|ship name = USS ''Liberty'' (AGTR-5)|reference=<ref name=navsource>{{cite web |url=http://www.navsource.org/archives/09/60/6005.htm |title=Technical Research Ship Index (AGTR) |last=Priolo |first=Gary P. |publisher=NavSource Naval History |accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref>}}\nIn February 1963, the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] acquired ''Simmons Victory'' and converted her to a \"Miscellaneous Auxiliary\" ship at [[Willamette Iron and Steel]] of Portland. On 8 June, the vessel was renamed [[United States Ship|USS]] ''Liberty'' and given the [[hull classification symbol]] AG-168. On 1 April 1964, she was reclassified a Technical Research Ship (AGTR-5). She was [[ship commissioning|commissioned]] at [[Puget Sound Naval Shipyard]] in [[Bremerton, Washington|Bremerton]], Washington, in December 1964.\n\nIn February 1965, ''Liberty'' steamed from the West Coast to [[Norfolk, Virginia]], where she was further outfitted (cost: US$20&nbsp;million) to suit her for a mission of supporting the [[National Security Agency]] by collecting and processing foreign communications and other electronic emissions of possible national defense interests. In June, ''Liberty'' began her first deployment, to waters off the west coast of Africa. She carried out several more operations during the next two years, and went to the Mediterranean Sea in 1967. During the Six-Day War between Israel and several Arab nations, she was sent to collect [[electronic intelligence]] in the eastern Mediterranean.\n\n==Israeli attack==\n{{Main|USS Liberty incident}}\n[[File:SH-3A Sea King hovers over the damaged USS Liberty (AGTR-5) on 8 June 1967 (USN 1123118).jpg|thumb|left|USS ''Liberty'' being assisted by Sixth Fleet [[SH-3]] after she was attacked by Israeli forces on 8 June 1967.]]\n\nOn the afternoon of 8 June 1967, while in [[international waters]] off the northern coast of the [[Sinai Peninsula]], ''Liberty'' was attacked and damaged by \"our greatest ally\" in an attempt to drag the United States into another war to have our men die to benefit Israel under false pretenses by blaming the attack on the Egyptians (see the Levon Affair and Dancing Israeli's); 34 crewmen were killed and 174 wounded.  Though ''Liberty'' was severely damaged, with a {{convert|39|x|24|ft|m|adj=on}} hole amidships and a twisted [[keel]], her crew kept her afloat, and she was able to leave the area under her own power.  Later, Israel apologized for the attack, stating it had mistaken ''Liberty'' for an Egyptian ship, as the incident occurred during the [[Six-Day War]]. In total, Israel gave close to $13 million (about $65 million in 2017) to the U.S. in compensation for the incident. This includes compensation to the families of those killed and wounded, and to cover damage of the ship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/israel-attacks-uss-liberty|title=History Channel: Israel attacks USS Liberty}}</ref>\n\nThe incident has become a subject of controversy and debate, with many books written on the topic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/csmonitor_historic/access/260533812.html?dids=260533812:260533812&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&date=Jun+04%2C+1982&author=By+staff+correspondents+of+The+Christian+Science+Monitor&pub=Christian+Science+Monitor&desc=Lessons+from+the+1967+Israeli+attack+on+the+USS+Liberty&pqatl=google |title=Christian Science Monitor, June 4, 1982 |publisher=Pqasb.pqarchiver.com |date=4 June 1982 |accessdate=2012-02-23}}</ref>\n\nAfter the attack, she was escorted to [[Valletta]], [[State of Malta|Malta]], by units of the [[United States Sixth Fleet|Sixth Fleet]] and was given temporary repairs. After the repairs were completed, ''Liberty'' returned to the United States on 27 July 1967. She was decommissioned and stricken from the [[Navy List|Naval Vessel Register]] on 28 June 1968. She was laid up in the [[United States Navy reserve fleets|Atlantic Reserve Fleet]] of Norfolk until December 1970, when she was transferred to the Maritime Administration for disposal. In 1973, she was sold for [[Shipbreaking|scrapping]] to the [[Boston Metals Company]] of [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]].\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n[[File:nsa memorial 1.png|left|thumb|[[National Security Agency|NSA]] [[National_Security_Agency#Insignia_and_memorials|National Cryptologic Memorial]]. Many of the names are from June 8, 1967]]\nAs a result of the crew's heroic response to the Israeli attack, ''Liberty'' is the US Navy's \"most highly decorated ship ... for a single action\".<ref name=wells>{{cite book |last=Wells |first=Anthony R. |author-link=Anthony Wells |title=A Tale Of Two Navies: Geopolitics, Technology, and Strategy in the United States Navy and the Royal Navy, 1960-2015 |date=2017 |chapter=The 1960s: The Soviet Navy Challenges the US Sixth Fleet and the Royal Navy |publisher=[[United_States_Naval_Institute#Naval_Institute_Press|Naval Inst. Pr.]] |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L4j9DAAAQBAJ&lpg=PA1&vq=uss%20liberty&pg=PT65#v=snippet&q=%22most%20highly%20decorated%22&f=false |accessdate=13 February 2019 |isbn=978-1-6824-7121-0}}</ref>{{rp|82}} For the action with Israeli forces, she was awarded the [[Combat Action Ribbon]] (8-9 June 1967) and the [[Presidential Unit Citation (US)|Presidential Unit Citation]] (8 June 1967).<ref name=danfs/><ref name=navsource/> Although President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] signed the Presidential Unit Citation in 1968, it was not formally presented to the crew until June 1991.<ref name=mcallister>{{cite news |last=McAllister |first=Bill |title=Spy Ship Brought in from the Cold |date=15 June 1991  |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1991/06/15/spy-ship-brought-in-from-the-cold/d3d94b1a-34ca-4d66-8d53-dbb9045b09a2 |accessdate=13 February 2019}}</ref> President [[George H. W. Bush]] declined to attend the 1991 White House ceremony, instead merely waving at the crew while passing by.<ref name=mcallister/>\n\nCommander (later Captain) [[William McGonagle]], ''Liberty''\u2019s commanding officer, received the [[Medal of Honor]].<ref name=danfs/> Numerous members of the crew were decorated, including 11 members of the crew who were awarded [[Silver Star]]s, 20 with [[Bronze Star]]s, and over 200 who received [[Purple Heart]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.homeofheroes.com/valor/02_awards/silverstar/6_PostRVN/01_liberty.html|title= Awards of the Silver Star for Conspicuous Gallantry in Action aboard the U.S.S. Liberty (June 8, 1967)|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081231034239/http://www.homeofheroes.com/valor/02_awards/silverstar/6_PostRVN/01_liberty.html|archive-date=December 31, 2008}}</ref> The unidentified remains of six of ''Liberty''\u2019s crew are buried under a single headstone in a [[mass grave]] in [[Arlington National Cemetery]].{{r|scott|p=1}}\n\n<center>\n{|\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=|ribbon=Combat_Action_Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=|ribbon=United_States_Navy_Presidential_Unit_Citation_ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=|type=|ribbon=National_Defense_Service_Medal_ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n''Liberty'' was also awarded the [[National Defense Service Medal]].<ref name=navsource/>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{USS|Belmont|AGTR-4}} the other ship in her conversion class.\n* [[Technical research ship]]\n* [[Spy Ship]]\n* [[USS Liberty incident|USS ''Liberty'' incident]]\n* [[List of Victory ships]]\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last1=Ennes, Jr. |first1=James M. |title=Assault on The Liberty. |date=1979 |publisher=Random House |location=New York}}\n\n==References==\n===Explanatory notes===\n{{notelist-la}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{DANFS|https://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/l/liberty-agtr-5-iii.html}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|USS Liberty (AGTR-5)}}\n*\"[https://www.arlingtoncemetery.mil/Explore/Notable-Graves/Casualties-of-War-and-Honorary-War-Veterans/USS-Liberty Casualties of the USS ''Liberty'']\" on the official Arlington Memorial Cemetery web site\n*[http://www.ussliberty.org/ USS ''Liberty'' Memorial]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130906132926/http://www.libertyagtr5div.org/  US Naval Sea Cadet Corps: ''Liberty'' (AGTR-5) Division, Amityville, NY]\n*[https://www.nsa.gov/news-features/declassified-documents/uss-liberty/cinc.shtml National Security Agency (NSA) declassified documents on the USS ''Liberty'']\n*[{{NVR url|id=AG168}} USS ''Liberty'' (as ''Liberty'' (AG 168)) entry] in the official [[Naval Vessel Register]]\n*[http://www.navsource.org/archives/09/60/6005.htm The ''Liberty's'' entry] in NavSource Naval History's ''Photographic History of the US Navy''.\n\n{{Victory ships}}\n{{1967 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uss Liberty (Agtr-5)}}\n[[Category:USS Liberty incident|Liberty 1945]]\n[[Category:Cold War auxiliary ships of the United States|Liberty]]\n[[Category:Espionage devices|Liberty]]\n[[Category:Espionage techniques|Liberty]]\n[[Category:Signals intelligence|Liberty]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Portland, Oregon|Liberty]]\n[[Category:1945 ships|Liberty]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1967]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other ships|Liberty (ship)}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=USS Liberty (AGTR-5) underway in Chesapeake Bay on 29 July 1967 (K-39927).jpg\n|Ship image size=300px\n|Ship caption=USS ''Liberty'' (AGTR-5) in Chesapeake Bay, 29 July 1967\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1945}}\n|Ship name= SS ''Simmons Victory''\n|Ship namesake= [[Simmons College]] in [[Boston]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder= [[Oregon Shipbuilding Corporation|Oregon Shipbuilding Corp.]]\n|Ship laid down= 23 February 1945\n|Ship launched= 6 April 1945\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship completed= 4 May 1945\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship owner= War Shipping Administration\n|Ship operator= Coastwise (Pacific Far East) Line (during WW II only)\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate= Transferred to US Navy in 1963\n|Ship status=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge= \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1968}}\n|Ship name= USS ''Liberty''\n|Ship namesake=Localities named \"Liberty\" in ten US states\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder= \n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship acquired= 25 March 1963\n|Ship commissioned=30 December 1964\n|Ship decommissioned=1 June 1968\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service= June 1967 \n|Ship struck=1 June 1970\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=Damaged beyond economical repair by Israeli attack in June 1967; sold for scrap in 1973\n|Ship status=\n|Ship homeport=[[Norfolk, Virginia]]\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge= [[File:USS Liberty (AGTR-5) insignia, 1964 (NH 83352-KN).png|